FortyTwo BBS Developer Documentation
====================================

Current status
--------------

FortyTwo BBS is currently pre-alpha software.

The public programming interfaces, extension points and compatibility
guarantees are still being designed and reviewed. Internal structures may
change before the first release.

Developers should not yet rely on undocumented functions, binary layouts,
database structures or internal file formats remaining stable.


Developer documentation plan
----------------------------

After the first public release, this document will provide a central entry
point for developers who want to extend FortyTwo BBS or build compatible
software.

The planned documentation includes:

- public interfaces and documented data formats
- development of Doors, clients and external tools
- Telnet, SSH, Fidonet and web integration
- directory structure and configuration files
- distinction between stable public interfaces and internal implementation
- coding standards and security requirements
- compatibility guarantees for extensions
- example programs and reproducible test environments


Extension goals
---------------

FortyTwo BBS is intended to provide a stable base for specialized clients,
Doors, administration tools and software for protected communication and
data exchange.

Extensions should be able to use documented interfaces without depending on
private implementation details.

Security boundaries, authentication, permissions, input validation and
backward compatibility will be part of the interface design rather than
being left to individual extensions.


Before the first release
------------------------

Until the public interfaces have been defined:

- treat all internal APIs and data structures as unstable
- do not assume binary compatibility between development versions
- do not modify production installations or valuable data
- use isolated test systems or disposable virtual machines
- document experimental interfaces clearly
- include tests with proposed interface changes


Contributing
------------

Development proposals should describe:

- the problem being solved
- the proposed public interface or data format
- security implications
- compatibility implications
- expected error handling
- test cases and example usage

